The 2008 financial crisis, also known as the global financial crisis (GFC) or the Panic of 2008, was a rather significant [financial crisis](/Financial_crisis) that had its roots firmly planted in the [United States](/United_States). Its causes were a murky cocktail of excessive [speculation](/Speculation) on property values, fueled by both homeowners and the very [financial institutions](/Financial_institution) meant to guide them. This led directly to the infamous [2000s United States housing bubble](/2000s_United_States_housing_bubble). To make matters worse, we had [predatory lending](/Predatory_lending) practices for [subprime mortgages](/Subprime_mortgages) and a rather spectacular failure in [regulation](/Regulation).

The party trick of [cash out refinancings](/Cash_out_refinancing) had artificially inflated consumption, a party that couldn't last when home prices inevitably began their descent. The initial phase, the [subprime mortgage crisis](/Subprime_mortgage_crisis), began its insidious crawl in early 2007. [Mortgage-backed securities](/Mortgage-backed_securities), those intricate financial instruments tied to the shaky ground of U.S. [real estate](/Real_estate), along with a vast, interconnected web of [derivatives](/Derivative_(finance)) linked to them, suddenly imploded. This [liquidity crisis](/Liquidity_crisis) didn't stay home; it spread like a contagion to global institutions by mid-2007, culminating in the rather dramatic [bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers](/Bankruptcy_of_Lehman_Brothers) in September 2008. That single event triggered a seismic [stock market crash](/Stock_market_crash) and a series of [bank runs](/Bank_run) across multiple countries. The crisis then poured gasoline on the already smoldering embers of the [Great Recession](/Great_Recession), a [global recession](/Global_recession) that had already begun its slow march in mid-2007. It also played a rather unfortunate role in the [2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis](/2008%E2%80%932011_Icelandic_financial_crisis) and the subsequent [euro area crisis](/Euro_area_crisis). A truly global performance of financial self-destruction.

### Background

The 1990s saw the [U.S. Congress](/U.S._Congress) pass legislation aimed at promoting [affordable housing](/Affordable_housing_in_the_United_States) through looser financing rules. Then, in 1999, parts of the [1933 Banking Act](/1933_Banking_Act) (the Glass–Steagall Act) were [repealed](/Gramm%E2%80%93Leach%E2%80%93Bliley_Act). This arcane legislative maneuver allowed institutions to blend the relatively safe world of [commercial banking](/Commercial_bank) and [insurance](/Insurance) with the inherently riskier realms of [investment banking](/Investment_banking) and [proprietary trading](/Proprietary_trading). A rather potent recipe for disaster, if you ask me.

As the [Federal Reserve](/Federal_Reserve) – the esteemed "Fed" – lowered the [federal funds rate](/Federal_funds_rate) from 2000 to 2003, institutions began to aggressively target low-income homebuyers, disproportionately from [racial minorities](/Racial_minorities), with high-risk loans. This alarming trend, however, seemed to escape the notice of the regulators. As interest rates began their ascent from 2004 to 2006, the cost of [mortgages](/Mortgage) climbed, and the insatiable demand for housing began to wane. By early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders started [defaulting](/Default_(finance)) on their payments, lenders began to buckle. The inevitable casualty was [New Century Financial](/New_Century_Financial), which filed for bankruptcy in April. With demand and prices continuing their downward spiral, the [financial contagion](/Financial_contagion) slithered into global [credit markets](/Credit_markets) by August 2007. Central banks, finally jolted into action, started injecting much-needed [liquidity](/Liquidity). Then, in March 2008, [Bear Stearns](/Bear_Stearns), the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was unceremoniously sold to [JPMorgan Chase](/JPMorgan_Chase) in a desperate "[fire sale](/Fire_sale)", propped up by Fed financing. The system was fraying at the edges.

In a rather dramatic response to the escalating crisis, governments worldwide scrambled to deploy massive [bailouts](/Bailout) for financial institutions, wielding [monetary policy](/Monetary_policy) and [fiscal policies](/Fiscal_policies) in a frantic effort to avert a complete [economic collapse](/Economic_collapse) of the [global financial system](/Global_financial_system). By July 2008, [Fannie Mae](/Fannie_Mae) and [Freddie Mac](/Freddie_Mac), entities that collectively owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, were on the verge of collapse. The [Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008](/Housing_and_Economic_Recovery_Act_of_2008) provided the legal framework for the federal government to seize them on September 7th. Then came [Lehman Brothers](/Lehman_Brothers), the fourth-largest U.S. investment bank, filing for the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history on September 15th. The very next day, the Fed was forced to bail out [American International Group](/American_International_Group), the country's largest insurer. And on September 25th, [Washington Mutual](/Washington_Mutual) was seized in what would become the largest bank failure in U.S. history. On October 3rd, Congress passed the [Emergency Economic Stabilization Act](/Emergency_Economic_Stabilization_Act), authorizing the [Treasury Department](/United_States_Department_of_the_Treasury) to gobble up [toxic assets](/Toxic_assets) and bank stocks through the $700 billion [Troubled Asset Relief Program](/Troubled_Asset_Relief_Program) (TARP). The Fed initiated its own brand of economic alchemy with [quantitative easing](/Quantitative_easing), purchasing treasury bonds and other assets. Then, in February 2009, President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) signed the [American Recovery and Reinvestment Act](/American_Recovery_and_Reinvestment_Act), a sprawling package of measures designed to preserve jobs and create new ones. These combined efforts, along with similar actions in other nations, managed to pull the world back from the absolute brink by mid-2009.

The precise impact of the crisis on the U.S. is still debated, but estimates suggest around 8.7 million jobs evaporated, pushing unemployment from a comfortable 5% in 2007 to a chilling 10% by October 2009. The poverty rate, predictably, climbed from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010. The [Dow Jones Industrial Average](/Dow_Jones_Industrial_Average) plummeted by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009. Some estimates even suggest that one in four households saw their [net worth](/Net_worth) shrink by 75% or more. In 2010, the [Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act](/Dodd%E2%80%93Frank_Wall_Street_Reform_and_Consumer_Protection_Act) was enacted, a monumental overhaul of financial regulations. Predictably, it faced opposition from many [Republicans](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) and was later softened by the [Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act](/Economic_Growth,_Regulatory_Relief,_and_Consumer_Protection_Act) in 2018. The global adoption of [Basel III](/Basel_III) capital and liquidity standards also followed.

