### Background

The world map, awash in browns indicating recession, tells a stark story of economic devastation in 2009. The share of the U.S. financial sector in the overall GDP, a graph that climbs steadily into the stratosphere before its dramatic fall, speaks volumes.

The crisis acted as a catalyst, or perhaps an accelerant, for the [Great Recession](/Great_Recession), a [global recession](/Global_recession) that had already begun its grim progression in mid-2007. It also cast a long shadow, contributing to the subsequent [euro area crisis](/Euro_area_crisis), which began with the [Greek government-debt crisis](/Greek_government-debt_crisis) in late 2009. And let's not forget the [2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis](/2008%E2%80%932011_Icelandic_financial_crisis), a catastrophic collapse that, relative to its economy's size, was the largest any country had ever endured. This was, without a doubt, one of the five worst financial crises in history, decimating the global economy by over $2 trillion. U.S. home mortgage debt, as a percentage of [GDP](/GDP), ballooned from a reasonable 46% in the 1990s to a staggering 73% by 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion. The relentless tide of [cash out refinancings](/Cash_out_refinancing), fueled by ever-increasing home values, had created a consumption binge that was utterly unsustainable once prices began to falter. Financial institutions found themselves drowning in investments tied to home mortgages, like [mortgage-backed securities](/Mortgage-backed_securities) and the complex web of [credit derivatives](/Credit_derivative) used to insure them. Their values plummeted. The [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund) estimated that major U.S. and European banks lost over $1 trillion on these [toxic assets](/Toxic_asset) and bad loans between January 2007 and September 2009.

The erosion of investor confidence in bank [solvency](/Solvency) and the drying up of credit led to a dramatic freefall in stock and [commodity](/Commodity) prices in late 2008 and early 2009. The crisis morphed into a global economic shockwave, triggering numerous [bank failures](/Bank_failure). Economies worldwide contracted as credit tightened and international trade dwindled. Housing markets buckled, unemployment soared, leading to a wave of [evictions](/Eviction) and [foreclosures](/Foreclosure). Businesses, unable to weather the storm, simply ceased to exist. U.S. household wealth, which had peaked at $61.4 trillion in the second quarter of 2007, evaporated by $11 trillion, leaving only $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009. This decline directly impacted consumption, which in turn led to a slump in business investment. The U.S. experienced a staggering 8.4% quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the fourth quarter of 2008. The unemployment rate hit an alarming 11.0% in October 2009, a level not seen since 1983, effectively doubling the pre-crisis rate. The average work week shrank to 33 hours, the lowest since data collection began in 1964.

The crisis, originating in the U.S., proved to be a global phenomenon. U.S. consumption had accounted for over a third of global consumption growth between 2000 and 2007, making the rest of the world rather dependent on the American consumer as a demand engine. The toxic securities, mind you, were held by investors worldwide. Derivatives like [credit default swaps](/Credit_default_swap) further intertwined the fates of major financial institutions. The process of [de-leveraging](/De-leveraging) – as institutions frantically sold assets to repay obligations they could no longer refinance in frozen credit markets – only accelerated the solvency crisis and choked off international trade. Developing countries felt the sting through falling trade, commodity prices, investment, and critically, [remittances](/Remittance) from their citizens working abroad. Nations with already fragile political systems watched nervously as Western investors pulled their capital.

In response, governments and central banks – the [Federal Reserve](/Federal_Reserve), the [European Central Bank](/European_Central_Bank), the [Bank of England](/Bank_of_England), among others – unleashed unprecedented trillions in [bailouts](/Bailout) and [stimulus](/Stimulus_(economics)). They employed aggressive [fiscal policy](/Fiscal_policy) and [monetary policy](/Monetary_policy) to counteract the slump in consumption and lending, trying to prevent a total collapse, encourage lending, restore confidence in the vital [commercial paper](/Commercial_paper) markets, stave off a [deflationary spiral](/Deflationary_spiral), and ensure banks had enough cash to meet customer withdrawals. In essence, central banks transitioned from being the "[lender of last resort](/Lender_of_last_resort)" to the "lender of *only* resort" for vast swathes of the economy. The Fed, in some eyes, became the "buyer of last resort." In just the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks injected $2.5 trillion into the credit market by purchasing government debt and troubled private assets. This was the largest liquidity injection and the most significant monetary policy action in history. Following the lead of the [2008 United Kingdom bank rescue package](/2008_United_Kingdom_bank_rescue_package), governments in Europe and the U.S. guaranteed bank debt and bolstered national banking systems, ultimately acquiring $1.5 trillion in newly issued [preferred stock](/Preferred_stock) in major banks. The Federal Reserve, to combat the [liquidity trap](/Liquidity_trap), resorted to creating substantial amounts of new currency.

Bailouts manifested as trillions in loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending. The controversy surrounding these bailouts, particularly the [AIG bonus payments controversy](/AIG_bonus_payments_controversy), spurred the development of various "decision making frameworks" to navigate the conflicting policy interests during such crises. Alistair Darling, the UK's [Chancellor of the Exchequer](/Chancellor_of_the_Exchequer) at the time, later remarked that Britain was mere hours away from "a breakdown of law and order" on the day the [Royal Bank of Scotland](/Royal_Bank_of_Scotland) was bailed out. Some banks, instead of domestic lending, redirected stimulus funds to more profitable ventures like emerging market investments.

By July 2010, the [Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act](/Dodd%E2%80%93Frank_Wall_Street_Reform_and_Consumer_Protection_Act) was signed into law in the United States, aiming to "promote the financial stability of the United States." Globally, [Basel III](/Basel_III) capital and liquidity standards were adopted. Since the crisis, U.S. consumer regulators have tightened their oversight of credit card and mortgage providers to curb the anti-competitive practices that contributed to the meltdown.

Two significant congressional reports scrutinized the crisis: the [Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission](/Financial_Crisis_Inquiry_Commission) report (January 2011) and the [United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations](/United_States_Senate_Homeland_Security_Permanent_Subcommittee_on_Investigations) report, "Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse" (April 2011).

In total, 47 bankers faced jail time as a consequence of the crisis, with over half hailing from [Iceland](/Iceland), the nation most severely impacted. In April 2012, Iceland's [Geir Haarde](/Geir_Haarde) became the sole politician convicted for his role. Only one U.S. banker, [Kareem Serageldin](/Kareem_Serageldin) of [Credit Suisse](/Credit_Suisse), received jail time for manipulating bond prices to conceal $1 billion in losses, earning a 30-month sentence and returning $24.6 million. No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted. [Goldman Sachs](/Goldman_Sachs) settled [securities fraud](/Securities_fraud) charges with a $550 million civil penalty, acknowledging incomplete marketing materials for CDOs after allegedly anticipating the crisis and selling toxic investments to clients.

With fewer resources available for [creative destruction](/Creative_destruction), patent applications remained flat, a stark contrast to the exponential growth seen in prior years.

The share of income going to the top 1% of earners, a key metric of economic inequality in the U.S., shows a disturbing upward trend from 1913 to 2008.

